Kant, too, regards both conversion and opposition as sylloyisms of the understandiny, the new judgment being always different in form, though not in matter, from the old. As regards conversion per accidens, the original proposition is clearly not identical with the converse; as it cannot be substituted for it, but may be false, while the converse is true. But on the new system of Sir W. Hamilton, the predicate being quantified, and the proposition reduced to an equation between the terms, it is better to consider the eonverted proposition as identical with the original.
